  "prompt": "Which sport can you start at the age of 26 to be a Olympian?",
  "response": "While starting a sport at the age of 26 and becoming an Olympian is quite ambitious, it is not impossible. Some sports are more accessible for late starters due to their unique characteristics, physical demands, and training structures. Here are a few sports where starting at 26 could still potentially lead to Olympic competition:\n\n1. **Archery**: Many successful archers begin training in their late teens or later. The sport requires skill, focus, and practice rather than peak physical fitness.\n\n2. **Sailing**: Sailing involves strategy, teamwork, and experience. Many sailors compete at a high level later in life after gaining experience.\n\n3. **Skiing (especially Freestyle or Snowboarding)**: Some disciplines in skiing and snowboarding may allow for late bloomers, particularly in freestyle events that value creativity and style.\n\n4. **Rowing**: While many rowers start young, there are examples of athletes who have started rowing later and gone on to compete at a high level.\n\n5. **Bobsledding**: This sport has seen athletes transition from other sports (like track and field or football) at later ages due to the physical strength required.\n\n6. **Weightlifting**: Similar to other strength sports, some athletes come to weightlifting later in life and excel after dedicated training.\n\nUltimately, success at the Olympic level often requires significant early training, but with dedication, proper coaching, talent, and the right path, it can be feasible in some sports.",
